ality as a great ideal can create such an unhealthy fascination t=\r\nhat is not idealized in any scriptures.\n    \n    The divinizing of Physical=\r\n body by Mahavatar Babaji is a scripture in itself, and since such a thing =\r\nis not being idealized by any scripture, it only means that: &quot;Scriptures ot=\r\nher than Vedas contain partial truth&quot;. \n    They talk about the highest tru=\r\nth, but only Vedic method, of worshipping divinity in its numerous forms, i=\r\ns the most complete expression of truth for all the creatures in all the pl=\r\nanes of existence. Such a worship would finally lead to divinization of Phy=\r\nsical body.\n\n&gt; &gt; (1) As I said, Yoga Vaasishtham and other scriptures tell =\r\nyou to unidentify with the body to realize higher realities. They do talk a=\r\nbout higher states beyond samdhi, but never tell you to think of the physic=\r\nal body as you attempt to realize.\n\n    Vedic method, worshipping the devat=\r\nas, allows for immortality, through Soma devata.\n\n&gt; &gt; (3) The ones in scrip=\r\ntures who actively pursued the divinization/immortalization of physical bod=\r\ny did not succeed. For example, king Trishanku wanted to ascend to the immo=\r\nrtal plane in his physical body. His family guru Maharshi Vasishtha refused=\r\n to help him. Maharshi Vishwamitra tried to help, but did not succeed!\n\n   =\r\n  OTOH, if one doesn&#39;t perform the yagna correctly, Indra doesn&#39;t allow the=\r\n ascent of mind, what to say of the body.\n\n&gt; All scriptures, whether it is =\r\nUpanishads or Yoga Vaasishtham, say that you overcome your self-identificat=\r\nion with the perishable body and identify with that which cannot be destroy=\r\ned. Then you are liberated.\n\n   Divinizing the Physical body itself will re=\r\nmove the sense of self-identification, Ahamkara, in any limited sense bound=\r\n to a Physical body of ones&#39; own possession or of the loved ones. No one ca=\r\nn attain liberation in Physical body, 